courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of the course, students should be able to:
1. Make the distinction between commercial entrepreneurship & social entrepreneurship, and demonstrate an understanding of the notion of social value proposition;
2. Recognize and reflect on the different and yet related concepts of social innovation, social entrepreneurship, social entrepreneurs and social enterprise;
3. Identify and delineate the core components of the social entrepreneurship process, and apply relevant theories to manage social enterprise;
4. Demonstrate an understanding of essential entrepreneurship skills including business modeling, business planning, financing and key management issues
5. Appreciate the challenges in scaling-up successful social programs and in realizing collective impact through effective cross-sector collaboration

The students will become more entrepreneurial in thinking and learn essential skills in managing social enterprises.

• To understand the historical development of global enterprises;

• To gain an appreciation for the complexities of the international challenges facing global enterprises;

• To discuss strategies for sequencing the penetration of countries and committing resources;

• To examine the major variables a global enterprise should consider when deciding whether and where to expand its operation;

• To explore international aspects of management (e.g. functions and strategies) in business operations

